obo:DOID_0050130 obo:IAO_0000115 Osmotic diarrhea is a dirrhea where diarrhea occurs when too much water is drawn into the bowels. This can be the result of maldigestion e.g., pancreatic disease or Coeliac disease, in which the nutrients are left in the lumen to pull in water. Osmotic diarrhea can also be caused by osmotic laxatives which work to alleviate constipation by drawing water into the bowels. In healthy individuals, too much magnesium or vitamin C or undigested lactose can produce osmotic diarrhea and distention of the bowel. A person who does not have lactose intolerance can have difficulty absorbing lactose after an extraordinarily high intake of dairy products.
